Updated Summary:
The research topic centers on the current challenges in traditional drug research methods, specifically the inherent difficulty in using multi‐omics approaches to systematically and macroscopically analyze the effects that drugs exert on the body. Traditional experimental designs often fall short because they tend to focus on isolated pathways or biomarkers, and inherent individual heterogeneity further complicates the ability to draw comprehensive, population‐level conclusions [1].
Recent discussions in the literature have highlighted that while traditional techniques have provided valuable insights at the molecular level, scaling these insights to capture the full systemic impact of drugs has proven extremely challenging. This is due in part to the fact that physiological responses to drugs are not linear or uniform across individuals, leading to significant variability that classical methods struggle to incorporate [1].
Against this backdrop, there is growing interest in exploring whether large-scale computational models—such as modern large language models (LLMs) and other deep learning frameworks—can be employed to simulate the complex interactions between drugs and the human body. These models are being considered for their potential to integrate diverse datasets, encompassing multi-omics data, electronic health records, clinical trial results, and other biomarkers, in order to construct more comprehensive simulations of drug effects [2]. The idea is that these large models could provide a systematic evaluation by:
•	Simulating drug-induced effects across multiple biological layers;
•	Accounting for individual variability and heterogeneity;
•	Providing insights into the complex network of interactions between various physiological systems in response to pharmacological interventions [2].
Preliminary findings suggested by recent research indicate that while the potential is promising, several challenges remain. Key among these challenges are the issues of data quality, the need for well-curated and standardized datasets, and the interpretability of the models’ outputs. In particular, the “black-box” nature of many large-scale models raises concerns with respect to understanding the causal relationships inferred in the simulation of drug responses, which could ultimately affect their clinical applicability [2].
Moreover, there is a recognition that the successful application of such models will depend on iterative improvements in both the underlying algorithms and the data integration techniques. Future research directions are likely to focus on:
•	Enhancing the interpretability of simulation outputs;
•	Developing robust validation frameworks to benchmark model predictions against empirical data;
•	Integrating more comprehensive datasets that capture not only molecular profiles but also clinical outcomes and environmental influences [2].
In summary, while traditional drug research has made significant strides at dissecting molecule-level interactions, the complexity of systemic drug effects and inter-individual differences necessitates new approaches. Large models hold promise in addressing these challenges by offering a platform for simulating drug impacts in a more holistic manner. However, realizing this potential will require overcoming substantial technical and methodological hurdles, including ensuring data fidelity, achieving model transparency, and establishing rigorous validation methodologies. This direction represents a significant evolution in the methodology for pharmacological assessments and could potentially transform drug development and personalized medicine in the future [1][2].

